Diagnosis (2026-06-24) and resolution
-------------------------------------

Both tests failed for two INDEPENDENT reasons.  Confirmed against the reference
implementation that runs both the reflector and the dkim2.com validator:
github.com/dkim2wg/interop, brong/lib/Mail/DKIM2/ (Common.pm, Verifier.pm,
MessageInstance.pm), per draft-ietf-dkim-dkim2-spec-02.

1. Message-Instance "header hash mismatch" (body hash matched)
   The MI header hash (Common.pm should_skip / spec 5.2) covers every header
   EXCEPT received, return-path, message-instance, dkim2-signature,
   dkim-signature, authentication-results, ^x-, ^arc-.  Two headers present at
   validation but absent when the reflector computed the hash were NOT skipped,
   so the recomputed hash differed:
     a. DKIM-Filter   -- added by our milter (SoftwareHeader).  OUR bug.
     b. Delivered-To  -- added by the local MDA (Dovecot LMTP) at final
                         delivery.  Not ours.
   The reflector even records what it signed: X-DKIM2-Info hn=content-type,date,
   from,message-id,mime-version,subject,to -- exactly the non-skipped set.

   FIX (a): the software header is now emitted as "X-DKIM-Filter" (the spec's
   own mechanism for proprietary trace headers; X- is skipped by 5.2).  See
   SWHEADERNAME in phoenixdkim.h.
   CAVEAT (b): Delivered-To is added after we run.  When pasting raw DELIVERED
   mail into the validator you MUST strip Delivered-To (and any other non-X-
   header the MDA adds) first, or capture the message at milter output instead
   of from the delivered mailbox.

2. "d=proteamail.com does not match mf domain dkim2.com" on the signature WE add
   Verifier.pm requires d= to relaxed-domain-match the mf= domain, AND mf= of
   hop N to match an rt= of hop N-1 (chain of custody).  We signed inbound
   final-delivery mail, so our signature had d=<our-domain> but mf=<external
   MAIL FROM> -- which can never align.  Signing belongs on outbound mail
   (originated or forwarded with MAIL FROM in our own domain); a final receiver
   verifies, it does not sign.

   FIX: DKIM2 signing is now gated on dfc->mctx_internal (outbound/authorized
   source) in dkimf_dkim2_eom().  Inbound mail is verified only.

Crypto itself was never at fault: the validator never rejected a signature
value, only the mf=/d= binding and the MI header hash.
